#Text=Charles Dieupart
#Text=Charles Dieupart ( after 1667 – 1740 ) was a French harpsichordist , violinist , and composer .
#Text=Although he was known as Charles to his contemporaries , his real name may have been François .
#Text=He was most probably born in Paris , but spent much of his life in London , where he settled sometime after 1702/1703 .
#Text=A prominent member of the Drury Lane musical establishment , Dieupart was active both as composer and performer and actively participated in the musical life of the city .
#Text=However , after about 1712 he earned his income mostly by teaching , and in his later years lived in poverty .
#Text=He is best remembered today for a collection of six harpsichord suites which influenced Johann Sebastian Bach 's English Suites .
#Text=Life
#Text=Details of Dieupart 's early life and training are sketchy , and the reason for his emigration to England is unknown .
#Text=The earliest document to refer to the composer is his own Six Suittes de clavessin , published in Amsterdam in 1701 .
#Text=He is next heard of on 11 February 1703 in London , when he performed Corelli 's music at Drury Lane with Gasparo Visconti .
#Text=Dieupart settled in London and eventually became an important member of the Drury Lane musical establishment .

#Text=He collaborated with playwright Peter Anthony Motteux , composer Thomas Clayton , and others ; he also participated in performances of music by Italian composers such as Giovanni Bononcini and Domenico Scarlatti . [ 1 ]
#Text=In late 1707 Dieupart became involved in establishing an operatic project at the Queen 's Theatre in the Haymarket , London .
#Text=Although he evidently played a significant part in the project , he was dropped by the management after about a year , in late 1708 .
#Text=Dieupart tried organizing a series of concerts at York Buildings in 1711 and 1712 , but ended up giving only a few .
#Text=After 1712 he was mostly active as a teacher , although his music was still performed in concerts until at least 1726 , and he was apparently a regular member of the Drury Lane orchestra .
#Text=Dieupart 's last known public appearance was in 1724 .
#Text=According to music historian John Hawkins , whose work is the most important source on Dieupart 's biography , the composer died at a very advanced age and in poverty . [ 1 ]
#Text=Music
#Text=Dieupart 's best-known work is Six Suittes de clavessin ( Amsterdam , 1701 ) .
#Text=As the title indicates , it contains six harpsichord suites .
#Text=All of them are in seven movements , always with the sequence ouverture – allemande – courante – sarabande – gavotte , a menuet or a passepied , and a gigue as the final movement .
#Text=Some of the movements are linked thematically .
#Text=The music represents a highly successful synthesis of French , Italian and English styles , married with imaginative harmony .
#Text=The same can be said about most of Dieupart 's other music , which has been neglected in recent times .

#Text=The suites were popular even during the composer 's lifetime : they were reissued already in 1702 , arranged for violin or recorder ( voice flute and fourth flute ) and basso continuo , and then 13 of the movements were published in London in 1705 as Select Lessons for the Harpsichord or Spinnett .
#Text=Johann Sebastian Bach copied all six suites sometime between 1709 and 1714 , [ 2 ] and was influenced by Dieupart 's music , particularly in the famous English Suites . [ 1 ]
#Text=Dieupart 's suites may have also inspired Nicolas Siret , whose first book adopts the suite 's initial opening as an example .
